<h1 id="overview">DocGen User Guide</h1>
<p>Everything you need to create templates, generate documents, and automate document workflows in Salesforce.</p>

<!-- ==================== GETTING STARTED ==================== -->

<div class="card">
    <h3>What is DocGen?</h3>
    <p>DocGen generates PDFs, Word docs, Excel spreadsheets, and PowerPoint decks by merging live Salesforce data into your templates. 100% native, zero external dependencies, runs entirely on the Salesforce platform.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="installation">Installation &amp; Setup</h2>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Install the package</strong> using the link from the <a href="/DocGenLanding">landing page</a> or GitHub. Choose "Install for Admins Only" to start.</li>
    <li><strong>Assign permission sets.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Permission Sets and assign <strong>DocGen Admin</strong> (full access) or <strong>DocGen User</strong> (generate only) to your users.</li>
    <li><strong>Enable Blob.toPdf() Release Update.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Release Updates and enable <em>"Use the Visualforce PDF Rendering Service for Blob.toPdf() Invocations"</em>. Without this, PDFs will show raw text instead of formatted content.</li>
    <li><strong>Add the component to record pages.</strong> Edit any Lightning Record Page, drag the <code>docGenRunner</code> component onto the layout, save and activate. Repeat for each object where users need to generate documents.</li>
    <li><strong>Open the DocGen app.</strong> Use the App Launcher to find "DocGen" — this is the Command Hub where admins create and manage templates.</li>
</ol>

<div class="warning">
    <strong>Required:</strong> The Blob.toPdf() Release Update must be enabled for PDF generation. Without it, PDFs render incorrectly. This is opt-in until Summer '26 when Salesforce enforces it for all orgs.
</div>

<h2 id="quick-start">Quick Start</h2>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Create a template.</strong> In the DocGen app, click Create New. Choose your object (Account, Opportunity, etc.), select fields, and upload a Word file with merge tags.</li>
    <li><strong>Add merge tags to your file.</strong> Type <code>{Name}</code> where you want the record name, <code>{Account.Name}</code> for a parent field, <code>{#Contacts}{FirstName}{/Contacts}</code> for child records.</li>
    <li><strong>Generate.</strong> Go to any record page with the DocGen component, select your template, and click Generate. Done.</li>
</ol>

<!-- ==================== TEMPLATES ==================== -->

<h2 id="creating-templates">Creating Templates</h2>

<p>Templates are created in the <strong>DocGen Command Hub</strong> (the DocGen app tab). The wizard walks you through three steps:</p>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Step 1 — Name &amp; Configure</h3>
    <p>Give your template a name, select the type (Word, Excel, or PowerPoint), choose the output format (PDF or Native), pick the base Salesforce object, and optionally add a category and description.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Step 2 — Select Fields (Query Builder)</h3>
    <p>Use the visual query builder to pick which fields appear in your document. Select base object fields, add parent lookups (e.g., Account.Name from an Opportunity), add child relationships (Contacts, Line Items), and even grandchild levels.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Step 3 — Upload Your File</h3>
    <p>Upload a <code>.docx</code>, <code>.xlsx</code>, or <code>.pptx</code> file containing merge tags. Use the <strong>Copy-Paste Tags</strong> tab to see all available tags and click to copy them into your template.</p>
</div>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> Set a <strong>Document Title Format</strong> in the template settings to auto-name generated files. Use merge tags like <code>Invoice_{Name}_{CloseDate}</code>.
</div>

<h2 id="query-builder">Visual Query Builder</h2>

<p>The query builder lets you configure which Salesforce data your template can access — no SOQL knowledge required.</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Base Fields</strong> — Check fields from the main object (Name, Email, Phone, etc.)</li>
    <li><strong>Parent Fields</strong> — Add related record fields via lookup (Account.Name, Owner.Email)</li>
    <li><strong>Child Relationships</strong> — Add child record lists (Contacts, OpportunityLineItems) with optional WHERE, ORDER BY, and LIMIT</li>
    <li><strong>Grandchild Levels</strong> — Nest relationships 3+ levels deep (Account &gt; Opportunity &gt; LineItems &gt; Schedules)</li>
    <li><strong>Manual Mode</strong> — Toggle to write SOQL directly for advanced users</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="report-import">Report Import</h2>

<p>Instead of building your query from scratch, import field configuration from an existing Salesforce Report:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>In the query builder, click <strong>Import from Report</strong>.</li>
    <li>Search and select any report (standard, cross-object, or custom).</li>
    <li>DocGen auto-detects the base object, fields, and date filters.</li>
    <li>Report filters are saved as <strong>Saved Queries</strong> for bulk generation.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="versioning">Template Versioning</h2>

<p>Every time you upload a new file, a new version is created. You can view version history, download any version, and restore a previous version at any time. The most recent upload is always the active version.</p>

<h2 id="import-export">Import &amp; Export Templates</h2>

<p>Move templates between orgs using the portable <code>.docgen.json</code> format:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Export:</strong> Click the row action menu on any template &gt; Export. Downloads a JSON file with all metadata, query config, and the template file.</li>
    <li><strong>Import:</strong> Click Import Template in the Command Hub, upload the JSON file. The template is recreated with all settings intact.</li>
</ul>

<!-- ==================== MERGE TAGS ==================== -->

<h2 id="field-tags">Field Tags</h2>

<p>Place tags in your Word, Excel, or PowerPoint template. DocGen replaces them with live Salesforce data at generation time.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Tag</th><th>What It Does</th><th>Example Output</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Name}</code></td><td>Insert a field value</td><td>Acme Corporation</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Email}</code></td><td>Any standard or custom field</td><td>john@acme.com</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Custom_Field__c}</code></td><td>Custom fields use API name</td><td>Gold Tier</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> The tag inherits whatever font, size, color, and style you apply to it in your template. Style the tag text to style the output.
</div>

<h2 id="parent-lookups">Parent Lookups</h2>

<p>Pull data from related records using dot notation:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Tag</th><th>What It Fetches</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Account.Name}</code></td><td>Parent Account's Name (from Opportunity, Contact, etc.)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Owner.Email}</code></td><td>Record owner's email address</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Account.Owner.Name}</code></td><td>Two levels up — Account's owner name</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="child-loops">Child Record Loops</h2>

<p>Repeat a section of your document for each child record. In Word tables, this duplicates the row for each record.</p>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="tag">{#Contacts}</span>
  Name: <span class="tag">{FirstName}</span> <span class="tag">{LastName}</span>
  Title: <span class="tag">{Title}</span>
<span class="tag">{/Contacts}</span>
</div>

<p>In a Word table, place <code>{#Contacts}</code> in the first cell of a row, field tags in the next row's cells, and <code>{/Contacts}</code> in a row below. Each Contact generates a new row.</p>

<h2 id="conditionals">Conditional Sections</h2>

<p>Show or hide content based on a field value:</p>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="tag">{#IsActive}</span>
  This customer is currently active.
<span class="tag">{/IsActive}</span>
</div>

<p>Works with checkbox fields (true/false) and any field that has a non-empty value. If the field is blank, null, or false, the entire section is removed from the output.</p>

<h2 id="formatting">Date &amp; Number Formatting</h2>

<table>
    <tr><th>Tag</th><th>Output</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{CloseDate:MM/dd/yyyy}</code></td><td>03/18/2026</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Amount:currency}</code></td><td>$500,000.00</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Rate:percent}</code></td><td>15.5%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Quantity:number}</code></td><td>1,234</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Price:#,##0.00}</code></td><td>1,234.56</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="aggregates">Aggregates (SUM, COUNT, AVG)</h2>

<p>Compute totals from child record lists. Place these <strong>outside</strong> the loop, typically below the table.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Tag</th><th>What It Does</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{SUM:QuoteLineItems.TotalPrice}</code></td><td>Sum of all line item totals</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{COUNT:Contacts}</code></td><td>Number of contacts</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{AVG:OpportunityLineItems.UnitPrice}</code></td><td>Average unit price</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{MIN:LineItems.Quantity}</code></td><td>Smallest quantity</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{MAX:LineItems.Quantity}</code></td><td>Largest quantity</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Add <code>:currency</code> or <code>:number</code> for formatting: <code>{SUM:LineItems.TotalPrice:currency}</code> renders as <strong>$55,000.00</strong>.</p>

<div class="tip"><strong>Zero extra SOQL</strong> — aggregates are computed from child data already in memory.</div>

<h2 id="images">Dynamic Images</h2>

<p>Insert images from Salesforce Files into your document. Store a ContentVersion ID (starts with <code>068</code>) in a text field, then reference it with the <code>%</code> prefix:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Tag</th><th>Behavior</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c}</code></td><td>Original image size</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:200x60}</code></td><td>Fixed: 200px wide, 60px tall</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:100%x}</code></td><td>Full page width, auto height</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:m100%x}</code></td><td>Max width (shrink to fit, never upscale)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:m100%xm50%}</code></td><td>Max width + max height constraints</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="barcodes-qr">Barcodes &amp; QR Codes</h2>

<p>Render scannable codes from any field value. <strong>PDF output only.</strong></p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Tag</th><th>Output</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*ProductCode}</code></td><td>Code 128 barcode (default size)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*SKU:code128:300x80}</code></td><td>Barcode at 300px x 80px</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*Website:qr}</code></td><td>QR code at 150px (default)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*TrackingUrl:qr:200}</code></td><td>QR code at 200px square</td></tr>
</table>

<p>QR codes support up to 255 characters. Both types render as pure CSS — no fonts or external services needed.</p>

<h2 id="rich-text">Rich Text Fields</h2>

<p>Rich Text Area fields automatically preserve formatting in output. Just use a standard tag — no special syntax needed:</p>

<div class="code-block"><span class="tag">{Description}</span>    <span class="comment">&lt;-- renders bold, italic, lists, images, links</span></div>

<p>Supported: bold, italic, underline, bulleted/numbered lists, hyperlinks, embedded images, tables. Works in both PDF and DOCX output. PowerPoint strips to plain text.</p>

<h2 id="page-breaks">Page Breaks in Loops</h2>

<p>Generate one page per child record by inserting a Word page break inside the loop:</p>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="tag">{#Opportunities}</span>
  Customer:  <span class="tag">{Account.Name}</span>
  Amount:    <span class="tag">{Amount:currency}</span>
  Close:     <span class="tag">{CloseDate:MM/dd/yyyy}</span>
               <span class="comment">&lt;-- Insert page break here (Ctrl+Enter in Word)</span>
<span class="tag">{/Opportunities}</span>
</div>

<p>Each Opportunity gets its own full page. Works with any child loop — invoices, receipts, certificates, packing slips.</p>

<!-- ==================== PDF FEATURES ==================== -->

<h2 id="headers-footers">Headers &amp; Footers in PDFs</h2>

<p>Headers and footers from your Word template carry into PDF output. They repeat on <strong>every page</strong> of the generated PDF.</p>

<ul>
    <li>Full formatting supported — bold, italic, colors, borders</li>
    <li>Merge tags work in headers and footers (<code>{Name}</code>, <code>{Account.Name}</code>)</li>
    <li>Images work in headers and footers</li>
    <li>Add them in Word: Insert &gt; Header or Footer</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="page-numbers">Dynamic Page Numbers</h2>

<p>Add "Page X of Y" numbering to your PDF headers or footers:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>In Word, double-click the header or footer to edit it.</li>
    <li>Go to <strong>Insert &gt; Page Number</strong> and pick a position.</li>
    <li>To add "of Y", go to <strong>Insert &gt; Quick Parts &gt; Field</strong> and select <code>NumPages</code>.</li>
    <li>Format the text around it: <code>Page [PAGE] of [NUMPAGES]</code>.</li>
    <li>Generate as PDF — the numbers increment dynamically on every page.</li>
</ol>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>New in v1.20:</strong> DocGen detects Word's PAGE and NUMPAGES field codes and converts them to dynamic CSS counters. Numbers update automatically as pages are added.
</div>

<h2 id="rtl">RTL Languages (Hebrew / Arabic)</h2>

<p>DocGen supports right-to-left text in PDF output:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Hebrew and Arabic characters render correctly using Arial Unicode MS</li>
    <li>Paragraphs with <code>&lt;w:bidi/&gt;</code> align right automatically</li>
    <li>Tables with RTL layout reverse column order</li>
    <li>Mixed content (Hebrew label + English merge value) works correctly</li>
</ul>

<div class="warning">
    <strong>Known limitation:</strong> Long RTL paragraphs that wrap to multiple lines may have continuation lines starting from the left. This is a Salesforce PDF engine limitation.
</div>

<h2 id="pdf-fonts">PDF Fonts &amp; Limits</h2>

<table>
    <tr><th>Supported Font</th><th>CSS Name</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Helvetica</td><td><code>sans-serif</code> (default)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Times</td><td><code>serif</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Courier</td><td><code>monospace</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Arial Unicode MS</td><td>CJK and Hebrew/Arabic</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Custom fonts are <strong>not supported</strong> in PDF output — this is a Salesforce platform limitation. If you need branded fonts, generate as DOCX and open in Word.</p>

<!-- ==================== DOCUMENT GENERATION ==================== -->

<h2 id="generate-single">Generate from a Record</h2>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>Navigate to any record page (Account, Opportunity, Contact, etc.).</li>
    <li>Find the <strong>Document Generator</strong> component on the page.</li>
    <li>Select a template from the dropdown.</li>
    <li>Choose <strong>Download</strong> or <strong>Save to Record</strong>.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Generate Document</strong>.</li>
</ol>

<p>If a default template is set for that object, it's pre-selected automatically.</p>

<h2 id="document-packets">Document Packets</h2>

<p>Generate multiple templates at once and merge them into a single PDF:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>Switch to the <strong>Create Packet</strong> tab in the Document Generator.</li>
    <li>Select multiple templates using the dual-listbox.</li>
    <li>Optionally include existing PDFs already on the record.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Generate Packet</strong> — all documents merge into one PDF.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="pdf-merge">PDF Merge &amp; Child Record PDFs</h2>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Merge Only</h3>
    <p>Combine existing PDFs on a record without generating from a template. Switch to <strong>Merge Only</strong> mode, select the PDFs, drag to reorder, and merge.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Child Record PDFs</h3>
    <p>Pull PDFs from child records and merge them. For example, from an Account, select the Opportunities relationship, filter with a WHERE clause (e.g., <code>StageName = 'Closed Won'</code>), browse PDFs grouped by child record, select the ones you want, and merge into one document.</p>
</div>

<p>All merging runs client-side in your browser — no size limits on the merged output.</p>

<h2 id="bulk-generation">Bulk Generation</h2>

<p>Generate documents for hundreds of records at once from the <strong>Bulk Generation</strong> tab in the Command Hub.</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Select a template</strong> and optionally preview with a sample record.</li>
    <li><strong>Enter a filter</strong> — a SOQL WHERE clause like <code>StageName = 'Closed Won' AND CloseDate = THIS_MONTH</code>. Click Validate to check syntax and see matching record count.</li>
    <li><strong>Configure the job</strong> — set batch size, output mode (individual files, merged packet, or both), and give it a name.</li>
    <li><strong>Submit</strong> — real-time progress tracking with auto-refresh. View results in Recent Jobs.</li>
</ol>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Saved Queries</h3>
    <p>Save frequently-used WHERE clauses with a name and description. Load them with one click when setting up future bulk jobs.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Bulk Merge</h3>
    <p>After a bulk job completes, click the merge icon on the job row to download all generated PDFs combined into a single file.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="giant-query">Giant Query (2,000+ Rows)</h2>

<p>DocGen automatically detects large datasets and switches to batch processing. Same template, same button — the complexity is invisible.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th></th><th>Standard Engine</th><th>Giant Query Engine</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>When</strong></td><td>&lt; 2,000 child records</td><td>&gt; 2,000 child records</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Detection</strong></td><td>Automatic</td><td>Automatic</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Speed</strong></td><td>2-5 seconds</td><td>1-5 minutes (async)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Output</strong></td><td>Download or save</td><td>Saved to record automatically</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Tested up to 28,000+ rows. Ideal for transaction logs, price books, audit trails, and bulk data reports.</p>

<!-- ==================== AUTOMATION ==================== -->

<h2 id="flow-actions">Flow Actions</h2>

<p>Three invocable actions for Salesforce Flow — use in Record-Triggered Flows, Screen Flows, and Subflows:</p>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Generate Document</h3>
    <p><strong>Input:</strong> Template ID, Record ID &nbsp; <strong>Output:</strong> Content Document ID</p>
    <p>Generates a single document synchronously. Use for automating document creation on record events.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Generate Bulk Documents</h3>
    <p><strong>Input:</strong> Template ID, WHERE Condition, Batch Size &nbsp; <strong>Output:</strong> Job ID</p>
    <p>Launches async batch generation. Returns a Job ID to poll for completion.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Giant Query Auto-Detect</h3>
    <p><strong>Input:</strong> Template ID, Record ID &nbsp; <strong>Output:</strong> Content Doc ID or Job ID</p>
    <p>Auto-detects dataset size. Under 2K rows: generates sync. Over 2K: launches async batch. Ideal for customer portals where dataset size is unknown.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="apex-provider">Custom Apex Data Provider</h2>

<p>For advanced use cases, implement the <code>DocGenDataProvider</code> interface to supply custom data from external APIs, computed fields, or cross-object aggregations. Select "Apex Provider" as the query type in the template configuration and specify your class name.</p>

<!-- ==================== ADMIN ==================== -->

<h2 id="permissions">Permissions &amp; Sharing</h2>

<table>
    <tr><th>Permission Set</th><th>Who</th><th>Access</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen Admin</strong></td><td>Template builders, admins</td><td>Full access — create, edit, delete templates, bulk generate</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen User</strong></td><td>End users</td><td>Generate documents, use templates (no admin)</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Field-level security is enforced — users only see fields they have permission to read. Record sharing follows standard Salesforce rules. Generated files are visible to anyone with access to the record.</p>

<p>Share individual templates with specific users, groups, or roles using the <strong>Share</strong> option in the template row action menu.</p>

<h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</h2>

<div class="card">
    <h3>PDF shows raw CSS text instead of formatted content</h3>
    <p>Enable the <strong>Blob.toPdf() Release Update</strong> in Setup &gt; Release Updates. This is the most common issue.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Images appear broken in PDF</h3>
    <p>Make sure the image field contains a ContentVersion ID (starts with <code>068</code>). The file must be committed (not just uploaded) in Salesforce Files.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Fields show as blank in output</h3>
    <p>Check that the field is included in the template's query configuration and that the running user has FLS access to the field.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Bulk generation is slow or hitting limits</h3>
    <p>Reduce batch size to 1 for complex templates with images or many child records. Each batch gets a fresh 12 MB heap limit.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Page numbers not showing in PDF</h3>
    <p>Use Word's built-in Insert &gt; Page Number feature (not typed text). DocGen detects the PAGE and NUMPAGES field codes automatically. Requires v1.20.0+.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Hebrew/Arabic text is blank in PDF</h3>
    <p>Ensure the Word template has RTL paragraph properties set (<code>&lt;w:bidi/&gt;</code>). DocGen auto-detects RTL and applies Arial Unicode MS font. Generate as DOCX if the PDF engine can't render specific glyphs.</p>
</div>

